docs.abstract: Continuing to shed his maverick credentials, the South Carolina Republican told his Democratic Senate colleagues, “What you want to do is destroy this guy’s life.”
docs.snippet: Continuing to shed his maverick credentials, the South Carolina Republican told his Democratic Senate colleagues, “What you want to do is destroy this guy’s life.”
docs.lead_paragraph: Senator Lindsey Graham, the blunt-speaking South Carolina Republican, vented to reporters on Thursday outside the hearing room where the Senate Judiciary Committee was hearing explosive testimony about sexual assault allegations against Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh, President Trump’s embattled Supreme Court nominee.

headline.main: Furious Lindsey Graham Calls Kavanaugh Hearing ‘the Most Unethical Sham’
headline.print_headline: Graham Erupts at ‘the Most Unethical Sham,’ Capping a Turn Toward Trump

docs.abstract: Senator John McCain lay in state in the Capitol’s Rotunda, hailed as a principled war hero as citizens wondered whether an era of comity died with him.
docs.snippet: Senator John McCain lay in state in the Capitol’s Rotunda, hailed as a principled war hero as citizens wondered whether an era of comity died with him.
docs.lead_paragraph: Senator John McCain lay in state on Friday in the Capitol whose halls he prowled for decades, hailed as a war hero, a principled lawmaker, and a restless fighter for his beliefs — and honored with a ceremony reserved for the country’s most revered figures.

headline.main: John McCain Lies in State in the Capitol: ‘We Lost a Good One’
headline.print_headline: Remembrances Honor a Senator’s Service and His Sacrifice

docs.abstract: President Trump, speaking Wednesday night in Estero, Fla., made inaccurate or disputed claims about the U.S. Embassy in Jerusalem, birthright citizenship and health care.
docs.snippet: President Trump, speaking Wednesday night in Estero, Fla., made inaccurate or disputed claims about the U.S. Embassy in Jerusalem, birthright citizenship and health care.
docs.lead_paragraph: President Trump’s claim of a $1 billion price cut conflates the cost of an interim facility and a high estimate for the cost of opening a permanent United States Embassy in Jerusalem. (Last December, he announced that he would move the embassy to Jerusalem from Tel Aviv; it opened in May.)

docs.abstract: In a lively argument, the justices considered internet privacy and whether payments to charities are a good way to settle class actions.
docs.snippet: In a lively argument, the justices considered internet privacy and whether payments to charities are a good way to settle class actions.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In a lively and freewheeling argument on Wednesday, the Supreme Court considered whether it should place limits on class-action settlements in which the plaintiffs’ lawyers receive millions and their clients get nothing. In the process, several justices mused about the nature of privacy in the digital age.

headline.main: Supreme Court Weighs Google Settlement That Paid Class Members Nothing
headline.print_headline: Supreme Court Weighs Google Settlement That Paid Class Members Nothing

docs.abstract: As President Trump tries again to use immigration fears for electoral advantage, this time with control of Congress at stake, Mr. Miller, his chief policy adviser, is at his side.
docs.snippet: As President Trump tries again to use immigration fears for electoral advantage, this time with control of Congress at stake, Mr. Miller, his chief policy adviser, is at his side.
docs.lead_paragraph: When self-inflicted damage left Donald J. Trump’s poll numbers sagging shortly after the Republican National Convention in 2016, the solution was to reframe the race around an incendiary issue that has animated Mr. Trump for decades: immigration.

headline.main: A Familiar Force Nurtures Trump’s Instincts on Immigration: Stephen Miller
headline.print_headline: Aide Who Whispered Immigration Agenda in Trump’s Ear Is Still at It

docs.abstract: Senator Charles E. Grassley and Jared Kushner ended a phone call with President Trump — and said the president will back a bipartisan criminal justice bill after the midterm elections.
docs.snippet: Senator Charles E. Grassley and Jared Kushner ended a phone call with President Trump — and said the president will back a bipartisan criminal justice bill after the midterm elections.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Senator Charles E. Grassley of Iowa said on Thursday that President Trump had committed to supporting a rewrite of the nation’s federal sentencing laws after November’s elections, breathing life into a long-stalled priority that has united an unlikely coalition of conservatives, libertarians and liberals.

headline.main: Senator Says He Has Trump’s Backing for Prison Bill Vote Late This Year
headline.print_headline: Trump Backs Effort to Reform Sentencing

byline.original: By Nicholas Fandos and Katie Rogers

docs.abstract: President Trump threatened to revoke “very soon” the security clearance of the little-known Justice Department official, who has been accused of having helped start the Russia investigation.
docs.snippet: President Trump threatened to revoke “very soon” the security clearance of the little-known Justice Department official, who has been accused of having helped start the Russia investigation.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump threatened on Friday to quickly revoke the security clearance of Bruce Ohr, a little-known Justice Department official, for the first time seeking to apply his power to cut access to sensitive information to a midlevel government worker rather than a prominent former national security official.

headline.main: Embracing Conspiracy Theory, Trump Escalates Attack on Bruce Ohr
headline.print_headline: President Aims Access Threat At New Target

docs.abstract: Unlike 1994 and its “Contract With America” or 2006 and its “Six for ’06,” this midterm campaign will not feature a centralized message from the party seeking control of the House.
docs.snippet: Unlike 1994 and its “Contract With America” or 2006 and its “Six for ’06,” this midterm campaign will not feature a centralized message from the party seeking control of the House.
docs.lead_paragraph: DALLAS — House Democrats, looking to wrest control of the chamber from Republicans in November, are discarding the lessons of successful midterms past and pressing only a bare-bones national agenda, leaving it to candidates to tailor their own messages to their districts.

headline.main: Democrats Discard Washington Platform in Bid for House Control
headline.print_headline: House Democrats Test a Do-It-Yourself Platform

docs.abstract: Mike Espy, former President Clinton’s agriculture secretary, could emerge as the top vote-getter in Mississippi’s Senate race on Election Day, but the runoff will be the hard part.
docs.snippet: Mike Espy, former President Clinton’s agriculture secretary, could emerge as the top vote-getter in Mississippi’s Senate race on Election Day, but the runoff will be the hard part.
docs.lead_paragraph: INDIANOLA, Miss. — When Mike Espy, a young black lawyer from a prominent local family, first campaigned for Congress in this tidy Delta town 30 years ago, many white voters refused to shake his hand. The onetime home of both B. B. King and the White Citizens’ Council, Indianola embodied the gulf that has divided Mississippi for centuries.

headline.main: A Black Senate Candidate Stumps in Mississippi, but His Party Holds Him Back
headline.print_headline: In Mississippi, a Long-Shot Democrat Tries to Transcend His Party

docs.abstract: This week has illustrated why Republicans put up with the chaos: As President Trump raged, his party moved toward an ideological shift in the Supreme Court that will last for decades.
docs.snippet: This week has illustrated why Republicans put up with the chaos: As President Trump raged, his party moved toward an ideological shift in the Supreme Court that will last for decades.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — On one end of Pennsylvania Avenue this week, President Trump and his closest advisers labored to beat back perceptions, fueled by an anonymous essay in The New York Times and a bruising new book by Bob Woodward, that he had all but lost control of the presidency from within. He lashed out anew at his attorney general, shouted “TREASON” and demanded investigations of his detractors.

headline.main: Congressional G.O.P. Agenda Quietly Falls Into Place Even as Trump Steals the Spotlight
